study_title: Effects of cadmium on honeybees
design: The abdomens of 6~8 bees for each replicate were pooled as a sample for the total RNA extraction using Trizol reagent (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, USA). After quantification and quality control, a total of 3 g of total RNA was prepared to purify the Poly (A) mRNA using poly-T oligo-attached magnetic beads (Invitrogen). The mRNA was broken down into small pieces by divalent cations under elevated temperature, which were used to generate the sequencing library using a mRNA-Seq sample preparation kit (Illumina, San Diego, USA) following the manufacturers instruction, and the average insert size of the paired-end libraries ranged from 250 bp to 350 bp. The library was sequenced on Illumina Novaseq 6000 platform (Illumina), and 150 bp paired-end reads were generated.

study_title: Apis mellifera ligustica Raw sequence reads
sample_description: capped frames of worker brood were shook vigorously to get rid of bees, and then kept in a humid incubator at 34 degree; every morning adult bees emerged from their cells were marked on the thorax with paint and returned to the hive. 21-day-old foragers were captured at the entrance of the source colony using soft forceps when marked bees of twenty-fist day have pollen loads on their hind legs.

study_title: Apis mellifera ligustica Raw sequence reads
sample_description: capped frames of worker brood were shook vigorously to get rid of bees, and then kept in a humid incubator at 34 degree; every morning adult bees emerged from their cells were marked on the thorax with paint and returned to the hive. 10-day-old nurses were collected from the hive when marked bees of tenth day entered the cells and were nursing the larvae.

study_title: Apis mellifera ligustica Raw sequence reads
sample_description: Newly emerged workers were obtained from capped brood frames brushed clear of bees when adult bees emerged from their cells for 3-4 h

study_title: Transcriptomic analysis for hygienic behavior in African-derived Apis mellifera honeybees
exp_title: RNA-seq of Apis mellifera: hygienic behavior
design: Libraries were prepared with TruSeq RNA sample preparation kit (Illumina) at the Iowa State University DNA Facility. Total RNA was purified to obtain the mRNA, using polyT oligoattached magnetic beads, and then fragmented it. RNA fragments primed with random hexamers was reverse transcribed into first strand cDNA using reverse transcriptase (SuperScript II) and random primers. Then the cDNA was converted into double stranded DNA and subjected to library preparation. The 10-dsDNA samples were attached to adapters for hybridization onto a flow cell and amplified by PCR. The quality of the libraries was controlled by an Agilent Technologies 2100 Bioanalyzer with Agilent DNA1000 kit. Before sequencing, all samples were normalized and pooled together using the adapter indices provided in the kit.  Samples were sequenced in single-end read mode (1x), with 100 bp reads, on a HiSeq 3000 machine (Illumina).
lab: LASA/Centro de Pesquisa de Sanidade Animal/Institu

study_title: RNAseq and ATACseq on honey bee queenless workers (whole brain)
exp_title: RNA-seq of Apis mellifera: adult worker brain
design: RNAseq libraries were constructed and sequenced by the W.M. Keck Center for Comparative and Functional Genomics at the Roy J. Carver Biotechnology Center (University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign). Libraries were constructed from 500 ng RNA per sample using the TruSeq Stranded mRNA HT kit (Illumina) on an ePMotion 5075 robot (Eppendorf). Libraries were uniquely barcoded, quantified, and pooled for sequencing across 6 lanes with 100 nt single-end sequencing on the Illumina HiSeq 4000.
lab: Program in Ecology, Evolution and Conservation Bio
isolation_source: University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign Bee Research Facility

study_title: Transcriptomic analysis of the honey bee (Apis mellifera) queen brain in response to pesticide exposure during development
design: 1. CONTAMINATED QUEEN CUPS WITH PESTICIDES: Plastic queen cups were coated with 200 mg of molten bees wax that was clean or mixed with pesticides in treatment groups. The pesticides used were: C (Control-No Pesticide), A (Amitraz-~46,820 PPB), CC (Chlorothalonil + Chlorphyrifos - 53,700:890 PPB), FC (Fluvalinate + Coumophos - 20,400:93,200 PPB). 2. GRAFTED LARVAE TO RAISE QUEENS: One-day-old worker larvae were carefully transferred to the wax-coated queen cups. Developing queen cells were then placed into queenless cell builders with nurse workers that reared the future queens. 3. TRANSFERED NEW QUEENS TO NEW COLONIES: Emerged queens were individually transferred to mating nucleus colonies to allow them to mate naturally and lay fertilized eggs. 4. CAPTUREED QUEENS AND ISOLATE BRAIN: Mated queens were sacrificed and brains were dissected into Direct-zol(TM). 5. RNA EXTRACTION: RNA isolated using Direct-zol(TM) and glycogen as a coprecipitator. Quantified via HS RNA Qubit 2.0.
biomaterial_provider: Brain_mRNA

design: 1. CONTAMINATED QUEEN CUPS WITH PESTICIDES: Plastic queen cups were coated with 200 mg of molten bees wax that was clean or mixed with pesticides in treatment groups. The pesticides used were: C (Control-No Pesticide), A (Amitraz-~46,820 PPB), CC (Chlorothalonil + Chlorphyrifos - 53,700:890 PPB), FC (Fluvalinate + Coumophos - 20,400:93,200 PPB). 2. GRAFTED LARVAE TO RAISE QUEENS: One-day-old worker larvae were carefully transferred to the wax-coated queen cups. Developing queen cells were then placed into queenless cell builders with nurse workers that reared the future queens. 3. TRANSFERED NEW QUEENS TO NEW COLONIES: Emerged queens were individually transferred to mating nucleus colonies to allow them to mate naturally and lay fertilized eggs. 4. CAPTUREED QUEENS AND ISOLATE BRAIN: Mated queens were sacrificed and brains were dissected into Direct-zol(TM). 5. RNA EXTRACTION: RNA isolated using Direct-zol(TM) and glycogen as a coprecipitator. Quantified via HS RNA Qubit 2.0.

GRAFTED LARVAE TO RAISE QUEENS: One-day-old worker larvae were carefully transferred to the wax-coated queen cups. Developing queen cells were then placed into queenless cell builders with nurse workers that reared the future queens. 3. TRANSFERED NEW QUEENS TO NEW COLONIES: Emerged queens were individually transferred to mating nucleus colonies to allow them to mate naturally and lay fertilized eggs. 4. CAPTUREED QUEENS AND ISOLATE BRAIN: Mated queens were sacrificed and brains were dissected into Direct-zol(TM). 5. RNA EXTRACTION: RNA isolated using Direct-zol(TM) and glycogen as a coprecipitator. Quantified via HS RNA Qubit 2.0.

study_title: Transcriptome analysis of Apis mellifera female embryos with fem gene knockout by CRISPR/Cas9
design: Total RNAs were extracted from the ovary and testis samples using Trizol Reagent (US Patent No.5,346,994). The extracted total RNA purity (OD260/280), concentration, nucleic acid absorption peak, and RNA integrity were detected using NanoDrop 2000 (Thermo Fisher Scientifc, Wilmington, DE) and Agilent Bioana lyzer 2100 system (Agilent Technologies, CA, USA). The mRNAs were then enriched using magnetic beads with oligo (dT) while being randomly interrupted in fragmentation bufer to construct the sequencing libraries.

The resulting fragments of RNA were sequenced using an Illumina HiSeq 2500 and yielded 100 base pair paired-end sequences. design: Total RNA was extracted using an RNeasy column (Qiagen). Total RNA integrity was confirmed with an Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer. RNA-seq libraries were prepared for the six samples using Illumina s TruSeq RNA Sample Preparation Kit as described in Corby-Harris et al. (2014). The resulting fragments of RNA were sequenced using an Illumina HiSeq 2500 and yielded 100 base pair paired-end sequences. The RNA was checked, the libraries were constructed, and the sequencing was performed at the University of Arizona UAGC (http://uagc.arl.arizona.edu/).

treatment: fed a control diet containing pollen and honey
study_title: Apis mellifera Transcriptome or Gene expression
exp_title: fat bodies from 3d bees fed control diet (honey and pollen)
design: Newly emerged bees (equal to or younger than 18 hours of age) were distributed among three replicate colonies. For each colony, bees were randomly distributed into each of two dietary treatments: a diet of honey and stored pollen (the control diet) or honey alone (pollen-restricted diet). Bees were restricted to each diet for a period of either 3 days or 8 days per colony for each diet. Fat bodies were isolated from five bees for each colony by diet by age combination and RNA was extracted using TriReagent according to the manufacturer's protocols. Total RNA integrity was confirmed using Agilents 2100 Bioanalyzer before the samples were subjected to RNA-seq TruSeq library preparation.    Each RNA-Seq library (a total of 12 libraries were sequenced for the study: 2 ages x 2 diets x 3 replicate colonies) were prepared using Illuminas TruSeq RNA Sample Preparation Kit according to the manufacturers protocols. Briefly, poly-A containing mRNA was purified using poly-T oligo-attached magnetic beads and was subsequently fragmented and primed for first-strand cDNA synthesis with random hexamer primers. After degrading the RNA template used for first-strand cDNA synthesis, synthesis of the second cDNA strand followed, yielding a double-stranded cDNA molecule. Adapters were ligated to both ends of the double-stranded cDNA molecules and adapter-ligated cDNAs were enriched using 15 cycles of PCR using adapter-specific primers. The libraries were validated according to the manufacturers protocol and the approximately 350 bp fragments were isolated from a 6% TBE PAGE gel and run through the Illumina sequencer for 2 x 100 cycles at a starting concentration of 12 pM per library.

study_title: LncRNA profile of Apis mellifera
exp_title: RNA-seq of Apis mellifera:common foragers from single-cohort colonies
design: Three g of RNA per honey bee sample was used as input material for RNA sample preparations. First strand cDNA was obtained using random hexamer primer and M-MuLV Reverse Transcriptase, second strand cDNA was obtained using DNA Polymerase I and RNase H. DNTPs with dTTP were replaced by dUTP in the reaction buffer. Remaining overhangs were converted into blunt ends by exonuclease/polymerase activities. After adenylation of 3 ends of DNA fragments, NEBNext Adaptor with hairpin loop structure were ligated to prepare for hybridization. AMPure XP system (Beckman Coulter, Beverly, USA) was used to purify the library fragments to select cDNA fragments of preferentially 150-200 bp in length. Lastly, products were purified (AMPure XP system) and library quality was assessed with the Agilent Bioanalyzer 2100 system. The libraries were sequenced on anIllumina Hiseq 2500 platform and 100 bp paired-end reads were generated.
lab: College of Animal Science and Technology
biomaterial_provider: Anhui Agricultural Uiversity

study_title: HGs and diet transcriptome
design: Total RNA was extracted from each sample using TriReagent (Invitrogen) according to the manufacturers specifications. RNA integrity was confirmed using Agilents 2100 Bioanalyzer. 4 lg of total RNA from each the six RNA sequencing (RNA-Seq) libraries were prepared using Illuminas TruSeq RNA Sample Preparation Kit. The sequencing libraries were validated and run through a 6% TBE PAGE gel. 50 bp fragments were isolated and run through the Illumina HiSeq 2000/2500 sequencer for 2  150 cycles at a starting concentration of 12 pM per library. All six samples were run on one lane.
sample_description: hypopharyngeal glands from bees fed pollen and honey
biomaterial_provider: V. Corby-Harris, USDA-ARS

exp_title: transcriptome of Apis mellifera hypopharyngeal glands
design: A  total  amount  of  3  g  RNA  per  sample  was  used  as  input  material  for  the  RNA sample preparations. Firstly, mRNA was purified, fragmentated. Secondly, cDNA strands were synthesized. Thirdly,150bp cDNA fragments were selected. Fourthly, PCR was performed with Phusion High-Fidelity DNA polymerase, Universal PCR primers and Index Primer.
lab: College of Animal Sciences (College of Bee Science
isolate: Newly emerged bees (< 24 h) were marked on their thoraxes with paint and put in a new hive. After 21 days, 21-day-old nurse bees were collected by opening the nest and identifying individuals keeping their heads and thoraxes inside of brood cells for at least 10 seconds from the new hive.

study_title: Apis mellifera Raw sequence reads
sample_description: For exploring the molecular mechanism of four honey bee (Apis mellifera) capping pheronmones (methyl palmitate, methyl oleate, methyl linoleate and methyl linolenate), We analyed the gene expression of non-capped (4 day), capping (6 day) and capped (8 day)honey bee worker and drone larvae to identify the biosynthetic pathways for these four pheromones in honey bee larvae. Six larval treatments including non-capped, capping and capped worker and drone larvae were sequenced by RNA-Seq and each treatment has 3 biological replicates.

study_title: transcriptome analysis of Apis mellifera mandibular glands from age-matched nurses and foragers
design: In brief, the mRNAs were enriched, fragmented into short pieces (about 300 nt) and reverse transcribed to cDNAs with a random hexamer primer and M-MuLV Reverse Transcriptase (RNase H-). Sequencing adaptors were ligated to the cDNA fragments through PCR amplification. Sequencing analysis was performed using HiSeq X Ten (Illumina, Inc. San Diego, USA), and 150 bp paired end reads were generated.
lab: College of Animal Sciences (College of Bee Science
isolate: Capped frames were sourced from five queen-right colonies and housed in an incubator at 34 C. Every morning, newly emerged bees (NEBs, < 24 h) were marked on their thoraxes with paint and put in a new hive. Markings continued for 5 days to make sure that the new hive could maintain its colony. NEBs were marked with different color each day so that we could easily distinguish the age of each worker and collect age-matched samples (10-day-old and 21-day-old) of nurse and forager bees. A total of > 12,500 NEBs from five colonies (about 2500 NEBs each) were labeled and placed into the new hive containing a young mated queen, a honey comb, a pollen comb, a larvae comb, as well as an empty comb for egg-laying. On the 21 day after emergence, 21-day-old nurses were collected by opening the nest and identifying individuals keeping their heads and thoraxes inside the brood cells for at least 10 seconds. The bees were anesthetized on ice, and HGs were dissected from bee heads using fine dissection scissors and a dissecting microscope.
strain: A. mellifera lingustica (Fengqiang No. 1 Italian honey bees)

study_title: Several species of phasmatodea, with a separate transcriptome set for each. Species: Aretaon asperrimus (Heteropterigidae), Sipyloidea sipylus (Diapheromeridae), and Medauroidea extradentata, Extatosoma tiaratum, and Ramulus artemis (Phasmatidae). Tr
design: The  midgut of the honeybee was dissected and the RNA was extracted using the TRIzol protocol. The barcoded library was generated using the Illumina TruSeq RNA kit and sequenced on one lane (along with the other libraries generated in this project). Paired-end sequencing was used. Each pair of files included here refers to the forward (1) and reverse (2) reads.
sample_description: Used to compare transcript number to genome number, see associated Phasmatodea data.
biomaterial_provider: Bee Biology

exp_title: Nasonov gland polyA RNA of Apis mellifera Nurse (Colony 3)

sample_title: Nasonov gland polyA RNA of Apis mellifera (Nurse)

biomaterial_provider: Harry H. Laidlaw Jr. Honey Bee Research Facility 1 Bee Biology Rd, Davis, CA 95616

study_title: Apis mellifera Raw sequence reads
sample_description: For exploring the molecular mechanism of four honey bee (Apis mellifera) capping pheronmones (methyl palmitate, methyl oleate, methyl linoleate and methyl linolenate), We analyed the gene expression of non-capped (4 day), capping (6 day) and capped (8 day) honey bee worker and drone larvae to identify the biosynthetic pathways for these four pheromones in honey bee larvae. Six larval treatments including non-capped, capping and capped worker and drone larvae were sequenced by DNA methylation and each treatment has 2 biological replicates

study_title: Transcriptional response of European foulbrood diseased Apis mellifera larvae
exp_title: RNA-Seq of Apis mellifera larva: Melissococcus plutonius infection EFB
design: Samples were collected on day 3 post infection (3 dpi) and day 6 post infection (6 dpi), respectively  Total RNA and DNA were sequentially isolated. Sampled individuals were homogenized in 300 l (3 dpi) and 600 l (6 dpi) extraction buffer, respectively. RNA was isolated using a NucleoSpin RNA purification kit (Macherey-Nagel, Dren, Germany) according to manufacturers protocol. Remaining genomic DNA was removed by digestion with TURBO DNase (Invitrogen, ThermoFischer Scientific, Paisley, United Kingdom). The Ribo-Zero magnetic kit (Epicentre Biotechnologies, Madison, WI, USA) was used to reduce the amount of bacterial-derived rRNA sequences. The NEBNext Poly(A) mRNA Magnetic Isolation Module (New England BioLabs, Frankfurt am Main, Germany) was used to remove eukaryotic-derived rRNA sequences. cDNA libraries were constructed with a NEBNext Ultra II RNA Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England BioLabs, Frankfurt am Main, Germany).  To assess quality and size of the libraries samples were run on an Agilent Bioanalyzer 2100 using an Agilent High Sensitivity DNA Kit as recommended by the manufacturer (Agilent Technologies, Waldbronn, Germany). Concentration of the libraries were determined using the Qubit dsDNA HS Assay Kit as recommended by the manufacturer (Life Technologies GmbH, Darmstadt, Germany).
sample_description: Infected with Melissococcus plutonius + Paenibacillus alvei
biomaterial_provider: Silvio Erler

study_title: The genetic underpinnings of Varroa mite and disease resistance in honey bees
design: Honey bees were collected in two batches from the brood box of standard Langstroth hives in wooden cages, where each cage consisted of 150300 bees, and transported to the laboratory. The boxes flash-frozen in liquid nitrogen and then stored at 80 C upon arrival. Whole-bee homogenates were made by macerating 100150 frozen honey bees per sampled colony in 15 mL of DEPC-treated water. RNA extraction was performed using the EcoPURE Total RNA Kit (ECOTECH Biotechnology, Erzurum, Turkey) according to the manufacturers protocol on 150 L of RNA per sample. The lysis buffer from the kit was mixed with -mercaptoethanol in a volume ratio of 100:1. An on-column DNase I treatment (EURx, Gdask, Poland) step was applied during RNA extraction according to the manufacturers protocol. Preliminary assessment of total RNA yield and purity, and integrity was done using NanoDrop 1000c spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA). RNA integrity was assessed by separation via electrophoresis for 35 min on 1% agarose gels mixed with 0.5% household bleach (6% sodium hypochlorite) prior to melting, and the Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer with the RNA 6000 Nano Kit (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA, USA) according to the manufacturers protocol without performing heat denaturation on RNA samples. First-strand cDNA libraries from captured mRNA were constructed and sequenced on Illumina NovaSeq 6000 (paired-end, 150 bp).
isolation_source: Brood box of standard Langstroth hives

The boxes flash-frozen in liquid nitrogen and then stored at 80 C upon arrival. Whole-bee homogenates were made by macerating 100150 frozen honey bees per sampled colony in 15 mL of DEPC-treated water. RNA extraction was performed using the EcoPURE Total RNA Kit (ECOTECH Biotechnology, Erzurum, Turkey) according to the manufacturers protocol on 150 L of RNA per sample. The lysis buffer from the kit was mixed with -mercaptoethanol in a volume ratio of 100:1. An on-column DNase I treatment (EURx, Gdask, Poland) step was applied during RNA extraction according to the manufacturers protocol. Preliminary assessment of total RNA yield and purity, and integrity was done using NanoDrop 1000c spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA). RNA integrity was assessed by separation via electrophoresis for 35 min on 1% agarose gels mixed with 0.5% household bleach (6% sodium hypochlorite) prior to melting, and the Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer with the RNA 6000 Nano Kit (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA, USA) according to the manufacturers protocol without performing heat denaturation on RNA samples. First-strand cDNA libraries from captured mRNA were constructed and sequenced on Illumina NovaSeq 6000 (paired-end, 150 bp).
isolation_source: Brood box of standard Langstroth hives

The boxes flash-frozen in liquid nitrogen and then stored at 80 C upon arrival. Whole-bee homogenates were made by macerating 100150 frozen honey bees per sampled colony in 15 mL of DEPC-treated water. RNA extraction was performed using the EcoPURE Total RNA Kit (ECOTECH Biotechnology, Erzurum, Turkey) according to the manufacturers protocol on 150 L of RNA per sample. The lysis buffer from the kit was mixed with -mercaptoethanol in a volume ratio of 100:1. An on-column DNase I treatment (EURx, Gdask, Poland) step was applied during RNA extraction according to the manufacturers protocol. Preliminary assessment of total RNA yield and purity, and integrity was done using NanoDrop 1000c spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA). RNA integrity was assessed by separation via electrophoresis for 35 min on 1% agarose gels mixed with 0.5% household bleach (6% sodium hypochlorite) prior to melting, and the Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer with the RNA 6000 Nano Kit (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA, USA) according to the manufacturers protocol without performing heat denaturation on RNA samples. First-strand cDNA libraries from captured mRNA were constructed and sequenced on Illumina NovaSeq 6000 (paired-end, 150 bp).
isolation_source: Brood box of standard Langstroth hives

The boxes flash-frozen in liquid nitrogen and then stored at 80 C upon arrival. Whole-bee homogenates were made by macerating 100150 frozen honey bees per sampled colony in 15 mL of DEPC-treated water. RNA extraction was performed using the EcoPURE Total RNA Kit (ECOTECH Biotechnology, Erzurum, Turkey) according to the manufacturers protocol on 150 L of RNA per sample. The lysis buffer from the kit was mixed with -mercaptoethanol in a volume ratio of 100:1. An on-column DNase I treatment (EURx, Gdask, Poland) step was applied during RNA extraction according to the manufacturers protocol. Preliminary assessment of total RNA yield and purity, and integrity was done using NanoDrop 1000c spectrophotometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA). RNA integrity was assessed by separation via electrophoresis for 35 min on 1% agarose gels mixed with 0.5% household bleach (6% sodium hypochlorite) prior to melting, and the Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer with the RNA 6000 Nano Kit (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA, USA) according to the manufacturers protocol without performing heat denaturation on RNA samples. First-strand cDNA libraries from captured mRNA were constructed and sequenced on Illumina NovaSeq 6000 (paired-end, 150 bp).
isolation_source: Brood box of standard Langstroth hives

tissue: whole larvae inoculated with B8 rep 1
study_title: Apis mellifera ligustica Transcriptome or Gene expression
exp_title: Apis mellifera larvae inoculated with P. apium B8 rep 1
design: Total RNA was extracted using TriReagent (Invitrogen). Total RNA integrity was confirmed with an Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer. A small aliquot (5  l) of the RNA was retained for rtPCR (see below). With the remaining RNA, RNA-seq libraries were prepared for the six samples using Illumina s TruSeq RNA Sample Preparation Kit as described in Corby-Harris et al. (2014). The resulting fragments of RNA were sequenced using an Illumina HiSeq 4000 and yielded 100 base pair paired-end sequences. The RNA was checked, the libraries were constructed, and the sequencing was performed at BGI Americas (https://www.bgi.com/us/).

With the remaining RNA, RNA-seq libraries were prepared for the six samples using Illumina s TruSeq RNA Sample Preparation Kit as described in Corby-Harris et al. (2014). The resulting fragments of RNA were sequenced using an Illumina HiSeq 4000 and yielded 100 base pair paired-end sequences. The RNA was checked, the libraries were constructed, and the sequencing was performed at BGI Americas (https://www.bgi.com/us/).

design: RNA extractions were made using TRIzol reagent (Invitrogen) following manufacturer instructions. Purity and concentration of RNA extracted from each sample was determined through optical absorbance at 260/280 nm using NanoDrop ND-1000 (NanoDrop Technologies). The RNA samples (2 g/per sample) were used for libraries preparation using TruSeq RNA sample preparation (Illumina) and a system of adaptors (barcodes). RNA samples were sequenced in an Illumina HiSeq 2500 equipment.

Purity and concentration of RNA extracted from each sample was determined through optical absorbance at 260/280 nm using NanoDrop ND-1000 (NanoDrop Technologies). The RNA samples (2 g/per sample) were used for libraries preparation using TruSeq RNA sample preparation (Illumina) and a system of adaptors (barcodes). RNA samples were sequenced in an Illumina HiSeq 2500 equipment.
